e Holocaust is furthermore increasingly understood as constitutive of a global memory community which transcends national memories and mediates universal values. The present volume diverges from this perspective by dealing also with everyday subjects of memory. This allows for a more complete view of the interdependencies between public and private memory and, more specifically, public and family memory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aContemporary History. 4aCultural History. 4aFamily. 4aHistory of the 20th Century. 4aHistory. 4aIdentity. 4aMemory Culture. 4aNarrative. 4aSocial Change. 4aTrauma. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aContemporary History.  aCultural History.  aFamily.  aHistory of the 20th Century.  aHistory.  aIdentity.  aMemory Culture.  aNarrative.  aSocial Change.  aTrauma.1 aBoesen, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoesen, Elisabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCarnegie, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Delyth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarstenauer, Rita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoffmann, Jeanette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJara, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoleva, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLentz, Fabienne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLohl, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMargue, Michel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMaslen, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb